When computing "sprint start" row on burndown chart the condition is checked:
{code:java}
BurndownTimelineProducer.addSprintStartTimelineEntry = function (data, time) {
        // give the consumer a chance to reset data
        data.statisticConsumer.beforeSprintStart(data);

        // create an entry for the current state
        var entry = BurndownTimelineProducer.getTimelineEntryForCurrentState(data, time);
        entry.initial = true;
        data.timeline.push(entry);

        // also set the max values
        data.maxValues = _.clone(data.currentValues);
    };

BurndownTimelineProducer.getTimelineEntryForCurrentState = function (data, time) {
        // put in the current status for accounted issues
        var issues = [];
        _.each(data.issueState, function (issue) {
            if (issue.isInChart) {
                issues.push(BurndownTimelineProducer.getCurrentState(data, issue));
            }
        });

        // setup a data point
        var timelineEntry = {
            time: time,
            issues: issues,
            values: _.clone(data.currentValues)
        };
        return timelineEntry;
    };

{code}
I think when computing the initial state the *if (issue.isInChart)* shouldn't be used (as it's only valid for the records inside the table - this assumes that scope has changed). instead the *issue.inScope* should be used here IMHO.

This bug is probably from the fact that the same code was initially used to determine changes to the scope (issue done, or moved from done to in progress) and it was taken to compute the initial state of sprint.

This is normally not a problem unless there is some mess in the issue history (I saw 1 issue regarding this on DoS previously)

 

also see

